  "title": "Explore",
  "body": " Explore    Explore: Significant Figures     Reinforce your ability to identify significant figures in real-world and scientific contexts.      This worksheet is designed to help you explore the concept of significant figures in physics.         It take the Moon about days to orbit Earth. How many significant figures are in this measurement?    Non-zero digits are always significant.    Three     has three non-zero digits: , , and . This counts as three significant figures.  So, has three significant figures.        The mean diameter of the Moon is about meters. How many significant figures are in this measurement?    All non-zero digits are significant. Leading zeros are not significant. Trailing zeros in a whole number without a decimal point are not significant.    Four     has four non-zero digits: , , , and . The trailing zeros after the are not significant because there is no decimal point or underline.  So, has four significant figures.        The mass of the Moon is about kilograms. How many significant figures are in this measurement?    All non-zero digits are significant. Zeros between non-zero digits are significant. Trailing zeros after a decimal point are significant.    Five     has four non-zero digits: , , , and . The zero occurs after a decimal so it is also significant.  So, has five significant figures.        The mean diameter of the Moon is about meters. Since the Moon is roughly spherical, we can calculate its volume using the formula: , where is the radius. Calculate the volume of the Moon and express your answer in scientific notation with the correct number of significant figures.    The 4 and 3 in the fraction are exact numbers, so they do not affect the number of significant figures. The radius is half the diameter, so meters. The given diameter has four significant figures, and we are multiplying it by itself three times in the volume formula, so the final answer should also have four significant figures.     , where m is the symbol for meters.     . Do not round yet, as we will keep all significant figures until the end.   .   .   .  Our original value of the diameter has four sig figs, and we are muliplying itself three time in the volume equaiton. So our volume should have four sig figs. .  Then the volume of the Moon is, meters cubed.        The mass of the Moon is about kilograms. The volume of the Moon is about, . The mass density of the Moon can be calculated using the formula: , where is the mass and is the volume. Calculate the mean density of the Moon and express your answer in scientific notation with the correct number of significant figures.    The mass has five significant figures, and the volume has four significant figures.          Let mass be represented by the sombol . So kilograms.  Let volume be represented by the sombol . So .  Mass density \" \" is given by the formula: .   .   .   .  The original mass has five significant figures, and the volume has four significant figures. The final answer should have the same number of significant figures as the measurement with the fewest significant figures, which is four.  So the mean density of the Moon is .        When an object falls near the surface of the Earth, ignoring air resistance, the object will have an acceleration of about meters per second squared. When an object falls near the surface of the Moon, the object will have an acceleration of about meters per second squared. Calculate the absolute value of the difference between the surface acceleration on the Moon and the surface acceleration on Earth.    Difference is calculated by subtracting the two values. The surface acceleration on the Moon has four significant figures, and the surface acceleration on Earth has three significant figures.     meters per second squared    The difference between the surface acceleration on the Moon and the surface acceleration on Earth is calculated by subtracting the two values:   meters per second squared. Note that the question didn't specify which value to subtract from which, so we can choose either order. If you subtract the surface acceleration on the Moon from the surface acceleration on Earth, you will get a positive value.  The absolute value of the difference is meters per second squared.  The surface acceleration on the Moon has four significant figures, and the surface acceleration on Earth has three significant figures. The final answer should have the same number of significant figures as the measurement with the fewest significant figures, which is three.  So the absolute value of the difference between the surface acceleration on the Moon and the surface acceleration on Earth is meters per second squared.      "
