  "id": "sec-prep-unit-prefixes",
  "level": "1",
  "url": "sec-prep-unit-prefixes.html",
  "type": "Section",
  "number": "4.1",
  "title": "Prep",
  "body": " Prep  This preparatory section will equip you with the knowledge and skills to wield units prefixes with confidence and precision. Through a combination of instructional video, explanatory text, and practice questions, you will become adept at all things unit prefixes.   Prep Videos: Units Prefixes  Watch the following video(s) to get an introduction to unit prefixes.   Great Example of Interference     Prep Text: Unit Prefixes  Read the following text to learn about unit prefixes. Don't forget to try the checkpoint questions along the way!   What Are Unit Prefixes?   Unit Prefix unit prefix    A modifier placed before a base unit to indicate a power-of-ten multiple or fraction of that unit. Unit prefixes provide a compact way to express very large or very small quantities. For example, the prefix kilo- means , so represents kilometers , or meters. Similarly, milli- means , so denotes milliseconds , or seconds.    Unit prefixes are the verbal runes that shrink or stretch your units with a single syllable. They're shortcuts to tame unwieldy measurements without changing their essence. Instead of writing out meters, you can invoke the prefix kilo- to conjure kilometers. Instead of whispering seconds, you can say nanosecond and sound like a seasoned chronomancer.  Prefixes are always attached to units, not to the raw numbers themselves. You won't hear \"nano\" on it's own; it always comes with a unit like \"meter\" or \"second.\" This is because prefixes are like magical modifiers that alter the scale of the unit, not the number itself.    Writing Prefixes and Their Symbols  If you want to use unit prefixes in your written spells, each prefix has its own symbol. For example, the prefix kilo- is represented by . A distance of  3   can be written more compactly as . Likewise, a time interval of  1   can be written as .   SI Unit Prefixes    Prefix Name  Symbol  Power of Ten  Decimal Name    quetta    nonillion    ronna    octillion    yotta    septillion    exa    quintillion    peta    quadrillion    tera    trillion    tera    trillion    giga    billion    mega    million    kilo    thousand    hecto    hundred    deca    ten    deci    tenth    centi    hundredth    milli    thousandth    micro    millionth    nano    billionth    pico    trillionth    femto    quadrillionth    atto    quintillionth    zepto    sextillionth    yocto    septillionth    ronto    octillionth    quecto    nonillionth     Note that there are also two ways to verbalize unit prefixes: the prefix name and the decimal name . The prefix name is the official SI term used in scientific contexts, like mega- or nano- . The decimal name is the everyday term that describes the quantity in more familiar terms, like \"million\" or \"billionth.\"      How would you say  73   in words?    The prefix is for mega, which means . The follows the prefix, and it stands for gram.     megagrams.    The prefix is for mega, which means . The follows the prefix, and it stands for gram. So  73   is megagrams. Or, if you prefer the decimal name, you could say million grams.       How would you say  22   in words?    nano is the prefix for , and the symbol for nano is .     nanoseconds.    nano is the prefix for , and the symbol for nano is . Seconds is the unit that follows the prefix nano. So  22   is nanoseconds. Or, if you prefer the decimal name, you could write billionths of a second.     Summary  You might wonder: if we can say “megagrams” instead of “a million grams,” why do we need both? The key is that they serve different roles in communication. The prefix name (like mega- ) is part of the official SI system. It's used when naming and writing units in scientific work: megameters, milliamps, nanoseconds. These are concise, precise, and standardized.  The decimal name (like “million”) isn't part of the unit itself, it's just how we describe the value of a number in everyday terms. You'll often hear it in speech, estimates, or media. Saying “a billion cells” or “a trillion dollars” is more natural for general audiences to understand compared to “gigacells” or “teradollars.”  So both ways are valid, but they're used in different contexts. And when you're fluent in both, you can navigate smoothly between scientific scrolls and everyday storytelling.  Bonus Trick: Poer of notation. When converting prefixed units to base units, you can use powers of ten to simplify the process. Each prefix corresponds to a specific power of ten. For example, turns into .    A Word of Caution  It's customary to not stack unit prefixes. For example, if you have million grams, you would not typically say kilokilogram, instead you would say megagrams or grams.  Be careful when communicating with synthetic beings, since unit prefixes used to represent different things in binary code. For example, kilobyte once used to be defined as bytes. However, those ancient scrolls have been updated to match our standard unit prefix notation. Now kilobyte is bytes, and kibibyte is bytes. It's best to extablish a common understanding before engaging in data transfer.    A Parting Word  A Parting Word  One prefix to scale them all, one prefix to name them, one prefix to tame them all, and with the units frame them.     Prep Questions: Unit Prefixes   Say outlout the following quantity.     How would you say in words?       centimeters.    Correct!       millimeters.    Your targeting system glitched, try again. The prefix milli means , and has the symbol .       meters.    Your enchanted click missed the mark, try again. This answer has no prefix. The prefix in the statement is the >.       decimeters.    Your digital blade missed the mark, try again. The prefix deci means , and has the symbol .         How would you say in words?       microamperes.    Correct!       megaamperes.    Your targeting system glitched, try again. The prefix mega means , and has the symbol .       milliamperes.    Your enchanted click missed the mark, try again. The prefix milli means , and has the symbol .       nanoamperes.    Your digital blade missed the mark, try again. The prefix nano means , and has the symbol .      Write the following quantity.     How would you write the value of terameter using the SI prefix symbol?           Correct!           Your targeting system glitched, try again. The symbol for tera is , not .           Your enchanted click missed the mark, try again. You have the unit for meter, but are missing the prefix.           Your digital blade missed the mark, try again. The prefix is for giga, which means .         How would you write the value of femtoseconds using the SI prefix symbol??           Correct!           Your targeting system glitched, try again. The symbol for femto is , not .           Your enchanted click missed the mark, try again. You have the unit for seconds, but are missing the prefix.           Your digital blade missed the mark, try again. The prefix is correct, but recall the SI unit symbol for seconds is , not .      Base Units and Scientific Notation     Convert the following quantity to base units and express it in scientific notation: .       .    Correct!       .    Your targeting system glitched, try again. The prefix is for giga, which means .       .    Your enchanted click missed the mark, try again. The prefix is for giga, which means .       .    Your digital blade missed the mark, try again. The prefix is for giga, which means .         Convert the following quantity to base units and express it in scientific notation: .       .    Correct!       .    Your targeting system glitched, try again. The prefix is for milli, which means .       .    Your enchanted click missed the mark, try again. The prefix is for milli, which means .       .    Your digital blade missed the mark, try again. The prefix is for milli, which means .       "
